liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Australian share market has shrugged off a slow start and is trading up 0.7 per cent at midday. The ASX 200 is being driven by consumer stocks, banks, and miners after iron ore prices surged overnight. Technology stocks and healthcare firms are taking a hit. Woolworths is up 5.1 per cent after its posted a rise in profit. Domino's Pizza has surged despite a big fall in profit because it is cutting 200 jobs and restructuring. Here are the top movers: IDP Education: +9.7 per cent to $25.53 Monadelphous: +9.4 per cent to $14.74 Domino's Pizza: +8.1 per cent to $51.92 WiseTech Global: -19.2 per cent to $70 Nanosonics: -9.2 per cent to $4.08 Illuka Resources: -7.4 per cent to $4.08

children.content: The Australian share market has shrugged off a slow start and is trading up 0.7 per cent at midday.
The ASX 200 is being driven by consumer stocks, banks, and miners after iron ore prices surged overnight.
Technology stocks and healthcare firms are taking a hit.

Domino's Pizza has surged despite a big fall in profit because it is cutting 200 jobs and restructuring.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Some other profit results out today: Logistics software company WiseTech Global saw net profit for 2023 rise by 9 per cent to $212 million. Their shares plunged because investors are disappointed by their forecast for 2024 earnings. Engineering firm Worley Parsons saw annual profit fall by 78 per cent to $37 million. IDP Education says net profit rose 45 per cent to $148.5 million for the year as student placement revenue increased to nearly $982 million as the international student market rebounded from COVID globally. Business travel management provider Corporate Travel Management says 2023 net profit rose from $3.2 million in 2022 to $77.6 million as revenue surged by 70 per cent as it gained new clients. But one of those clients is the United Kingdom, which is controversially paying CTM $3 billion to provide temporary housing for asylum seekers including on a barge in Dorset. "In April 2023, CTM was awarded its largest customer contract, to manage the accommodation needs of asylum seekers in the United Kingdom." "It is expected to contribute significantly to the Europe region's results in future years."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Oil and gas giant Santos has also reported its half-yearly earnings this morning, with its profit after tax down by almost a third to $US790 million ($1.23 billion). Last year, Santos reported a half-year profit of $US1.17 billion. The company's production volume was down by 13% to 45 million barrels of oil equivalent, and sales volume also fell by 15% to 41.7 million barrels of oil equivalent. Sales revenue also fell by 21 per cent, which Santos said was the result of lower realised prices for oil and gas. Despite the fall in profits, Santos will pay a dividend of 8.7 US cents per share, which it says is 14% higher than the previous year's results.
